8 poll results that show Donald Trump is serious
Some have tried to label him a weather vane.
Others consider him just a joke.
Some are waiting for collapse.
While some Republicans have tried to yank Donald Trump out of the top spot in support polls, it hasn't (yet) been successful.
In ten of the most recent 11 national polls, Donald Trump has been leading by double digits, and some are beginning to seriously consider what this means for the real estate king's nomination chances.
Of course, the parliamentary term is still in its early stages.
These results do not yet mean that Trump is likely to become the Republican nominee.
Commentators point out that at this point in 2011, Rick Perry was losing the lead to the rising Herman Cain, neither of whom got behind any states in the nomination process.
There are also many reasons why he would have problems in general elections.
However, outside groups such as Jeb Bush's Super PAC and the conservative financial organization Club for Growth have noted Trump's persistence and have begun using their funds to topple him.
The following recent support poll results suggest that the real estate king is not just a passing phase:
Trump's popularity ratings have done an about-face.
Just before Donald Trump announced his candidacy in mid-June, Monmouth University polls showed that only two out of ten Republicans were positive about the real estate king.
By mid-July, the figure was 40 percent.
At the beginning of August, the figure was 52 percent.
Currently, six out of ten Republicans have a positive view of Donald Trump.
About three out of ten say they have a negative attitude.
These numbers are also true in the first primary states.
In a poll conducted by Quinnipiac University in Iowa last week, 60 percent of Republicans said they were sympathetic to Trump.
Two-thirds of Republican voters would be happy if Trump became the nominee.
In a CNN/ORC poll last week, 67 percent of Republicans said they would be either "excited" or "satisfied" if Trump were the nominee.
Only two in ten said they would be "shocked" if he became a candidate.
Only Ben Carson generates roughly the same level of enthusiasm as Trump (43 percent "enthusiastic" vs. Trump's 40 percent).
The next most exciting?
Marco Rubio with only 21%.
On the other hand, 47 percent of Republican voters would be "dissatisfied" or "shocked" if Jeb Bush, the establishment's favorite, were to become the nominee.
Trump's fiery nature is not a problem for most Republicans.
While Donald Trump has been widely criticized for his pompous rhetoric and insults, according to Monday's ABC News/Washington Post poll, 52 percent of Republican-leaning voters at the national level think the real estate king has a character befitting a president.
According to a Quinnipiac poll last week, in the state of Iowa, which is holding its first party convention, the figure is the same: 52 percent of Republicans think Trump has the right temperament for a leader.
However, according to an ABC/Post poll, 44 percent think his character is not suitable for being president, and nearly six in ten think his character does not belong in the White House.
Republican voters are getting used to the idea.
When Republican voters think like commentators, they think Trump is the real option.
According to a CNN/ORC poll, four out of ten said Trump was the most likely choice when asked who is most likely to be nominated as the Republican nominee.
As recently as the end of July, four out of ten supported Jeb Bush.
Disclosure: Republican Party voters haven't always had access to the brightest crystal ball possible.
At this time in the last legislature, four out of ten Republicans thought Rick Perry would be nominated, with only 28 percent supporting the final nominee, Mitt Romney.
In any case, this shows that the majority of Republican Party voters find Trump's campaign credible.
Even if Republicans aligned themselves with the other candidate, Trump would still win nearly every one.
Some commentators have pointed out that the fragmented field has likely contributed to Trump's leadership, as anti-Trump support is split among numerous other candidates.
However, a poll conducted by Monmouth University in early September showed that in a hypothetical bilateral race between Trump and nearly all other Republican candidates, Trump gets majority support in almost all cases.
She leads Carly Fiorina with 13 points, Marco Rubio with 14 points, Walker with 15 points, Jeb Bush with 19 points, and Rand Paul, John Kasich and Chris Christie with 33 points each.
He is tied on points with Ted Cruz.
The only candidate to beat Trump?
If they were pitted against each other, Ben Carson would beat businessman Trump by a large margin of 18 points.
Barely a majority of Donald Trump's supporters have said they have made the decision.
A new CBS/NYT poll from Tuesday shows that just over half of pro-Trump voters have decided who their vote goes to.
Of course, the situation can change, and no one can say with absolute certainty that they will never change their mind.
46 percent said they could potentially change candidates.
In any case, Trump's biggest rival right now is another unlikely winner, neurosurgeon Ben Carson, but voters who said they made a decision are twice as likely to side with Trump.
Six out of ten Republicans say they agree with Trump on immigration.
Ever since Donald Trump called Mexican immigrants "rapists" two months ago in his campaign launch speech, immigration has been at the center of the 2016 debate.
Some worry that Trump's bombast will drive Latino voters away from the Republican Party and hurt rebranding efforts.
According to a new ABC/Post poll released Monday, six out of ten Republicans say they agree with Trump on immigration issues.
So it seems that as long as immigration is at the center of things, so will Donald Trump.
Frustration with the government has reached a new height.
Support for Donald Trump and Ben Carson now accounts for about half of Republican voters, largely due to their position outside politics.
Six out of ten Republicans said in Monday's ABC/Post poll that they would rather choose someone outside politics than one with government experience.
They are also angry with the federal government.
A Des Moines Register/Bloomberg poll from Iowa two weeks ago showed that three out of four Iowa Republicans are frustrated with Republicans in Congress: 54 percent are "dissatisfied" and 21 percent are "really angry."
Jeremy Corbyn's first appearance at Prime Minister's Question Time
Corbyn's first appearance at Question Time has been eagerly awaited since his election
The new leader of the Labour Party, Jeremy Corbyn, faces David Cameron for the first time during Prime Minister's Question Time.
Corbyn rises to ask the first of his six questions shortly after noon, and it is likely that both the media and Labour MPs will be watching his performance closely.
Corbyn has called for "less theatre and more facts" for this weekly show.
He has also said that he could leave some of the events to his colleagues.
This encounter will be the first parliamentary test for Corbyn's leadership since he was appointed to the shadow cabinet and spoke at the annual meeting of the Confederation of Trade Unions on Tuesday.
Meanwhile, the Labour leader's decision to stand silent during the national anthem at Tuesday's memorial service, which took place on the 75th anniversary of the Battle for Britain air war, has sparked criticism from Conservative MPs and appeared in several front-page stories.
Corbyn's decision not to sing the national anthem has attracted attention
A spokesman for Corbyn said he "stood respectfully silent" and that he acknowledged "the bravery of the Royal Air Force in the British air war."
Owen Smith, a member of Corbyn's shadow government, told BBC Two's Newsnight that he would have urged the Labour leader to sing the national anthem despite his belief that the Royal House should be abolished.
Nearly a dozen shadow ministers have refused to be part of Corbyn's inner circle, citing differences over economic, defence and foreign affairs. Initially, less than a sixth of the parliamentary party supported him as leader.
BBC politics correspondent Robin Brant says policy differences over the party's status in the European Union and the government's subsidy cap have also "piled up" within the Labour Party since Corbyn's appointment.
Corbyn said at a meeting of the Confederation of Trade Unions that Labour would propose an amendment that would remove the entire roof.
Hours later, Mr Smith, the shadow government's secretary for work and pensions, said the party was "quite clear" that they were only opposed to the government's plans to lower the ceiling from £26,000 to £23,0000.
Corbyn becomes the fifth Labour leader David Cameron has faced in the last decade he has been leader of the Conservative Party.
The Labour leader has promised a new approach to politics and now says he has "crowdsourced" ideas into questions for the Prime Minister and received more than 30,000 proposals.
Islington North MP Corbyn has said the nature of the Prime Minister's Question Time is too confrontational and that he will refrain from both witty rhetoric and banter, promising instead to focus on serious issues such as poverty, inequality and the challenges faced by young people.
Corbyn has said Angela Eagle, the shadow government's finance secretary, will deputise for him during Question Time when Corbyn is not attending - for example, when Cameron is abroad.
Mr Corbyn has also suggested that other colleagues could sometimes be allowed to speak, and he has said that he has approached the Speaker of the House of Commons, John Bercow, about the matter.
When Cameron took over in 2005, he said he wanted to move away from the kind of political theatre often associated with Prime Minister's Question Time, but he later had to admit that he had failed.
Since they began to be televised in 1990, Question Time with the Prime Minister has been an important measure of the leader's judgment, his control of the House of Commons, and his position among other MPs, although critics have criticised Question Time as nothing more than a caricature requiring far-reaching reforms.
