Pound sterling rises as UK wage growth accelerates
The value of the pound jumped upwards after the numbers showed an upward trend in UK wage growth, while the FTSE 100 index rose along with bidding target SABMiller.
Between May and July, UK wages, excluding bonuses, rose by 2.9 per cent compared to the same period last year.
The growth rate was the fastest since 2009 and was considered to bring with it estimates of price increases.
The pound rose more than one percent against the dollar to $1.5505, and 0.84 percent against the euro to 1.3730 euros.
The FTSE 100 index closed up 1.49% at 6229.21.
SABMiller was the most distinctive stock on the market, gaining 20 percent after being approached by rival AB InBev with an offer.
The agreement would bring together two of the world's largest breweries and bring together brands such as Budweiser, Stella Artois, Peroni and Grolsch.
Burberry's stock rose 0.9 percent after encouraging news emerged from rival luxury goods group Richmont.
Richemont's latest sales figures were not only better than expected, but also showed that sales in China - a key market for Burberry - had started to grow again.
Glencore's shares rose 5% after the mining giant said it had raised $2.5 billion by issuing shares as part of its debt-cutting strategy.
Shares of packaging and paper group Mondi were the biggest decliners in the index at 4.3% after Goldman Sachs changed its recommendation for the company to "sell."
JD Sports rose 3.1 per cent after the sportswear company announced its half-year pre-tax revenue: an 83 per cent increase to £46.6 million.
According to the head of JD Sports, higher salaries could hurt expansion
Peter Cowgill, chief executive of JD Sports, says if the minimum wage for workers is raised in the UK, it could mean "more purchasing power for potential consumers".
However, this purchasing power is unlikely to outweigh the higher labor costs incurred by the company, Cowgill notes.
The costs could fall on the company's expansion plans, he added, which would mean fewer additional jobs.
Metcash launches grassroots campaign against Aldi's intrusion
Metcash is trying to protect its IGA trades from Aldi's invasion in South and Western Australia.
Food wholesaler Metcash has launched a grassroots campaign to defend IGA traders' market share in South and Western Australia ahead of Aldi's $700 million attack.
Aldi is preparing to open two distribution centres and a first store early next year in South and Western Australia, with up to 120 stores to come. Meanwhile, Metcash and IGA supermarkets are strengthening their relationships with local food retailers and building the IGA brand through mainstream and social media marketing, as well as events like the Adelaide show.
IGA retailers and suppliers have jumped in, with brands like Dunsborough-based ice cream maker Simmo's offering tastings in IGA stores, and shop owners selling discounted tickets to Australian football matches to their regular customers.
Metcash is expected to reveal more details about its defensive strategy on September 29 when this food, alcohol and hardware wholesaler hosts its annual investor strategy day.
There's a lot at stake, as South and Western Australia together account for nearly 30% of Metcash's IGA trading area, with higher profit margins than Metcash's IGA network in the eastern states.
Shopping visitors in South and Western Australia are notoriously parochial, and IGA retailers have a much larger market share than New South Wales, Victoria and Queensland: more than 30 per cent in the South and 24 per cent in the West, compared to 14 per cent in the East.
However, analysts like Morgan Stanley believe Aldi will grab about 5 percent of the food market in the two states within 12 months of opening its first stores. Turnover comes from all operators, but mainly from independent retailers.
In a report this week, Morgan Stanley analyst Tom Kierath estimated that IGA dealers could lose $360 million annually in sales and Metcash could lose $250 million by the end of 2016.
This forecast is based on the assumption that Aldi will open 25 stores in the south and 30 stores in the west next year, generating revenues of $ 500 million and $ 600 million in these areas, respectively.
The loss of food and food sales and quantities at Metcash's high fixed cost base could cost Metcash about $13 million in pre-interest and tax losses in operating profits, Kierath said.
At the same time, Metcash is losing market share in the eastern states, mainly to Aldi and Coles, although a recent study by Roy Morgan found that IGA's customers were the most loyal.
Morgan Stanley expects Metcash's food and food sales to decline 3.8 percent in 2016; 4,1 % in 2017 and 2,1 % in 2018, reducing its market share from 14 % in 2015 to 10,3 % in 2020.
Last week, Hamish Douglass, manager of a leading investment fund and founder of Magellan Financial Group, said at a business lunch in Melbourne that Metcash could "very possibly disappear in a decade".
Metcash has declined to respond publicly to Douglass' comments.
However, it is understood that Douglass was contacted by a member of Metcash's board of directors last week.
IGA's market share has decreased from 18% in 2010 to 14%, and revenues from Metcash's food and beverage business, which supplies approximately 1200 IGA retailers, have fallen by 43% since 2012. This indicates a reduction in debt financing for operations as sales and margins are under pressure.
However, the wholesaler stands its ground and has invested more than $150 million annually in lowering prices for hundreds of products weekly to the same level as Coles and Woolworths, helping IGA retailers renovate stores by adding faster growing fresh food, and bringing to market a better selection of private-label products.
Metcash CEO Ian Morrice says lowering prices and improving stores have increased traction, and he hopes the wholesaler will return to the path of revenue growth in 2017, the first time in four years.
Australian Tennis Federation president Steve Healy backs Thanasi Kokkinakis
Thanasi Kokkinakis deserves credit rather than criticism for his behavior
Thanasi Kokkinakis has suffered as a bystander in a recent storm that has raged around her friend Nick Kyrgios. He deserves credit rather than criticism for his own behaviour," said Australian Tennis Association president Steve Healy.
Kokkinakis, a younger member of the talented duo known as "Special Ks", unwittingly went public for an incident in which Kyrgios annoyed Stan Wawrinka at the Montreal Masters.
Shortly thereafter, in a fiery qualifying match in Cincinnati, the head referee had to fire Kokkinakis and his opponent Ryan Harrison twice when Harrison declared, "Wawrinka should have beaten Kyrgios, and I should beat that brat."
While Kokkinakis was last seen breaking his racket after a cramp ruined his eventual win over Richard Gasquet at the US Open, Healy has been a staunch defender for Kokkinakis.
Right now, the youngster is in Glasgow competing with Sam Groth for second place in singles matches with Bernard Tomic in the Davis Cup semi-final against Great Britain.
"I feel pretty strongly that Thanasi has just been dragged into the brawl," Healy said.
He broke his racket when he lost to a cramp at the US Open, but he's not the first player to break his racket when frustrated, and I know Thanas well enough to know he's not proud of it.
But he has behaved very well, including in quite provocative situations at the US Open with Harrison and so on, and I think he deserves praise.
He's got a great team around him, he's got a great family around him and I think he's been treated a little harshly.
He is very mature for 19, he works hard, he fits into the team and so on, and he has never had problems with other players. He is respected in the dressing room, he trains hard, he is in good shape and he is a very calm and mature young man, and I think he should be judged on his merits.
Healy has also supported the decision not to include Kyrgios in important games starting on Friday, describing this "joint decision" as a good decision for everyone, but still supporting the Canberra's return to the team's regular lineup.
"We want the team to be fully focused on the games and not all the controversy around [Kyrgios]," Healy said.
And Nick has risen really fast, as Federer and Murray, for example, have pointed out, and he's growing up in the public eye, and he's made some horrible mistakes and deserves all the criticism he gets. But we're trying to support him, we're trying to help him understand the consequences of what he's done, and I think it's best for both the team and him if he spends some time out of the public eye thinking about those consequences.
European migration crisis: Hungary declares state of emergency, closes borders, arrests migrants
