This is what happens when the Federal Reserve raises interest rates
Interest rates will rise, and markets with rising rates will crash, bond yields will rise, and the economy will fall into recession.
This is what we know.
What we don't know is how long all this will take or how long it will take.
The past does not help much in terms of timing, especially when it comes to the economy.
The recession has sometimes lasted only 11 months since the first drawdown, sometimes as long as 86 months.
The Federal Reserve's aggressiveness in raising interest rates has often, though not always, been a determining factor in how the economy and financial assets react.
That is why Federal Reserve officials have so vigorously stressed that investors should not focus on when interest rates will start to rise, but rather on the trajectory of the time it takes for the situation to normalize.
Indeed, there are several variables in the equation.
Eventually, however, market participants may discover that all the fuss surrounding the rate hike has been excessive.
"The central bank's first hike since the global economic crisis will inevitably be interpreted in some circles as the end of the era of 'cheap money,'" said Julian Jessop, chief economic adviser on global affairs at Capital Economics, in a message to clients.
What we do not expect, however, is that the gradual return of US interest rates to normal, albeit still low, levels will be the kind of cataclysmic shock that many seem to fear.
However, this does not mean that it does not have an impact.
Below is a look at how some parts of the economy will react based on past developments:
As the market has seen over the past month or so, waiting for an interest rate hike can make the situation volatile.
When the increase becomes a fact, the effect is not quite so dramatic.
"It appears that return on capital tends to stop for 12 to 24 months after the first hike, which again potentially reflects a lag in monetary policy," analysts at Deutsche Bank said in a recent study of what happens after the central bank hike.
More specifically, over the past 35 years or so, the market is generally on a strong upward trajectory of about 14 percent as we approach a hike, 250 days after that the situation is fairly flat (average increase of 2.6 percent), and normality has been reached after 500 days with an average return of 14.4 percent in the last six cycles, according to a recent analysis by Bob Doll, chief equity strategist at Nuveen Asset Management.  which was published in Barron's magazine.
According to Deutche Bank, the impact on equities tends to be more pronounced later in the upward cycle, when yields begin to fall.
Recessions are part of economic life, but interest rate hikes often contribute to their coming.
In the current situation, the central bank is facing certain challenges that have not existed in the past and that could accelerate a recession.
This is particularly the case for gross domestic product, which will be closest to its all-time low before the central bank's interest rate hike.
According to Deutsche Bank, in 118 withdrawals since 1950, nominal annual GDP has only twice been below 4.5%.
While the figure was 3.6 percent in the second quarter of 2015, few believe it will hold up after the third quarter has advanced by 1.5 percent, according to the Atlanta Federal Reserve Bank.
Raising interest rates in such a fragile economic setting can be risky and raises the question of "whether this time will be different", Deutsche Bank said.
Market participants have been preparing for a central bank hike throughout the year, and everyone is looking forward to this week's Federal Open Market Committee meeting, which ends Thursday.
While many strategists and economists believe the committee can approve a raise at this meeting, futures trading only anticipates a 25% probability.
"Our study shows that since 1950, all mark-up cycles have so far occurred in increasing leverage supercycles, where GDP has passed its pre-recession peaks very quickly after stimulus has begun," the report says.
On the other hand, there has now been an exceptionally slow recovery from the recession, which has been the worst of the observation period.
In the current cycle, the central bank has waited by far the longest for the last recession to end: the record has been 35 months and it is now in its 74th month.
Fixed yields have also been volatile as markets wait for an interest rate hike, and the pattern is somewhat reminiscent of capital observations.
The main difference is that when a central bank changes course, its effects are more quickly reflected in bonds than in equities.
The direction of bond yields appears to change immediately at the first increase/cut of the cycle.
At the end of the increase cycle, bond yields will fall immediately," Deutche Bank said.
Charles Schwab strategists believe that raising interest rates will cause yields on longer- and shorter-term bonds to converge, thereby flattening the yield curve.
High-yield bonds often perform better in such a situation, although "we are still cautious about looking for returns," said Kathy Jones, a fixed yield analyst at Schwab, in an analysis.
Surprisingly, Jones believes markets have already adjusted to the central bank's policy expectations.
"In addition to the strength of the dollar and falling inflation expectations, there are several signs that markets have adjusted to the outlook for tighter monetary policy," he wrote.
Short-term interest rates are high, the yield curve is flatter, credit margins have increased and volatility has increased - all these are characteristic of markets at a time when the central bank has tightened its policy.
In general, companies with predominantly U.S. businesses win when interest rates rise and local products become more attractive.
Multinationals with high levels of debt perform worse when the rise in the value of the dollar makes their products more expensive on the world market and their debt becomes more expensive than they have financed.
"History shows that 'quality' stocks tend to be more profitable in the three months after the first rate hike," Goldman Sachs analysts said in a report to clients.
Enterprises with strong turnover overtook enterprises with weak turnover after increases in 1994, 1999 and 2004 by an average of five percentage points.
Companies with high returns on capital and low volatility stocks performed better than lower-quality firms. The average for the former was 4 (percentage points) and for the latter 3 (percentage points).
Debt becomes a big problem.
Those companies with a lot of variable rate debt are losing the most, Goldman said.
Outside of stock market speculation, consumers also have the opportunity to benefit from the rise in the value of the dollar.
Savers can also make a profit with higher returns, although experts disagree on how quickly the effect will be felt.
