I guess David Cameron knows the Lorax better than this?
Every parent soon learns one thing: if your child loves a book, it won't be long before they learn it almost by heart.
Unless you're David Cameron.
When a holiday childcare service asked the prime minister about his favourite children's book, he chose Dr Seuss's The Lorax, an environmental protection story published in 1971.
It was a tricky choice, Cameron writes in a post on SuperCamps' website, adding: "Funny, moving, creative and carries a strong message. I enjoy reading this book to my children because it always seems to have a picture or message that we haven't seen before."
All of this is true, but the next paragraph, in which Cameron supposedly describes the plot of the book, is a summary of the 2012 film version, in which new characters and details were added to fill the rather short original text.
"In the walled city of Tarville, where all nature has disappeared and even air is a commodity, the boy Ted hopes to win the heart of the girl of his dreams by fulfilling Audrey's wish to see the right tree," the text says, describing a love story not written by Dr Seuss, real name Theodor Seuss Geisel, who died in 1991.
If that's not suspicious enough, Cameron's text sounds in places like it was taken from the plot synopsis of the movie Lorax found on the Internet Movie Database website, which begins as follows: "In the walled city of Tarville, where everything is artificial and even air is a commodity, Ted the boy hopes to win the heart of the Audrey girl of his dreams."
Given that Cameron is a publicly active parent, it seems unlikely that he would be so unfamiliar with the plot of the book. In it, a young, nameless boy learns how local nature has been destroyed by the greedy, tree-chopping and weaving Kerskanen, ignoring the short, mustachioed creature that gave the story its name, the Lorax, who "speaks for the trees."
Such a relatively invisible PR task is probably outsourced to an assistant who, apparently, has never read a book 20 times in a row to a child.
A spokesman for the prime minister said the text may have come from Cameron's constituency office.
SuperCamps confirmed that the text was received from Cameron's staff, but did not comment further at the time.
