Experts criticise Public Health England's e-cigarette review
Researchers have said that the government-funded agency's claim that e-cigarettes are 95% less harmful than traditional cigarettes originated from a meeting of 12 people, some of whom had connections to the tobacco industry.
Experts writing for the British Medical Journal (BMJ) agreed with the Lancet, criticizing the evidence used by Public Health England (PHE) in its report on e-cigarettes.
PHE released this "milestone" report last month, describing it as a "comprehensive review of the evidence."
However, several researchers have questioned the sustainability of the data, pointing to links between some experts and the tobacco industry.
Last month, the medical journal The Lancet published an editorial attacking the "exceptionally shaky foundation" of PHE's main conclusion.
Two other researchers who have written in the BMJ have wondered whether the claims are "built on rock or sand."
Martin McKee, Professor of European Public Health at the London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine, and Simon Capewell, Professor of Clinical Epidemiology at the University of Liverpool, say: "The main principle of public health is that policies should be based on proven effectiveness."
They say the public expects PHE's claim that "according to the current best estimate, e-cigarettes are about 95% less harmful than conventional cigarettes" is based on a detailed evaluation and modelling of the evidence.
In fact, it comes from one meeting of 12 people where a multi-criteria decision analysis model (MCDA) was developed to synthesize their opinion on the harms associated with various nicotine-containing products, and the results of this meeting were summarized in research.
McKee and Capewell say one of the sponsors of the meeting was a company called EuroSwiss Health, whose chief executive reportedly previously received funding from Bristish American Tobacco for an independent study.
He also supported the BAT's public health mandate in the sustainability report, they say.
One of the 12 people at the meeting said they had received funding from an e-cigarette manufacturer, but not the funding he reportedly received in the past from tobacco company Philip Morris International, they added.
The selection criteria for the panel members are not disclosed, but the panel includes several well-known e-cigarette advocates, some of whom also say in the study that they have received funding from the field.
Others present are not known for their expertise in tobacco control.
The meeting was also attended by PHE's Director of Tobacco.
The study produced by the group "eloquently admits" that there is a lack of "irrefutable evidence regarding harm in most products and most criteria," McKee and Capewell write.
However, none of these links or limitations are mentioned in the PHE report.
McKee and Capewell say PHE's claims that "so far there is no evidence that e-cigarettes serve as a route to smoking in children or non-smokers" are premature.
Professor Kevin Fenton, director of health and wellbeing at PHE, says claims made in the BMJ have been answered before.
He says, "E-cigarettes are significantly less harmful than smoking."
Half of those who burn their lifespan die of addiction.
All the evidence suggests that the health risks posed by e-cigarettes are comparatively small, but we must continue to study the long-term effects.
PHE has a clear duty to inform the public about what evidence shows and what it does not show, especially when there is so much public uncertainty about the relative dangers compared to tobacco.
Nearly 80,000 people die each year from smoking-related illness and smoking costs the NHS £2 billion a year.
By explaining the current evidence - that is, although e-cigarettes are not risk-free, their harm is only a fraction of that of conventional tobacco - we are fulfilling our national responsibility.
