"Sound genetics" allows brain cells to be controlled by sound waves
The video shows how nematodes change direction as soon as a sound impulse hits them.
Scientists have bred worms with genetically engineered nervous systems so that they can be controlled by sound wave bursts.
Tiny nematodes change direction as soon as they are hit by a sound impulse that is too high for human ears to hear.
The impulses work by switching on genetically engineered motor neurons with membrane channels that respond to ultrasonic waves.
Related: Scientists read and write brain activity with light
The researchers said the worms show that a new method called sound genetics works. In it, ultrasound can be used to activate certain brain, heart and muscle cells from outside the body.
Sreekanth Chalasani, a researcher at the Salk Institute in La Jolla, California, told The Guardian that the method could one day replace deep brain stimulation. It is an invasive procedure in which electrical impulses are introduced into people's brains to treat Parkinson's disease.
Nematodes do not normally respond to ultrasound, but Chalasani found that when surrounded by a liquid with microscopic bubbles, the situation changed.
He noticed that the bubbles amplified ultrasonic waves, which then pass inside the worms.
Amplified ultrasonic waves act on TRP-4 ion channels, structures found in the cell membranes of some worms.
Sound waves cause these ion channels to open and activate the cells attached to them, according to a report published in the journal Nature Communications.
To make ultrasonically controlled nematodes, Chalasani genetically modified the worms so that some of their motor neurons have TRP-4 ion channels.
When Chalasani applied ultrasound to the modified worms, the microbubbles amplified the sound waves and transmitted them to the worms, where they turn on the modified motor neurons.
The method shares some features with optogenetics, a groundbreaking tool that allows scientists to turn neurons on and off using light impulses.
However, Chalasani says that the use of sonogenetics may have some advantages over optogenetics.
Unlike light, which must be sent via optical fiber to a desired location inside the brain, low-frequency ultrasound waves can pass through the tissue unhindered, so they can be sent to the brain from the top of the skull.
"We believe that using gene therapy and a therapeutic virus, it may be possible to make targeted human neurons momentarily respond to an ultrasound signal in certain neurological treatments in a clinical setting," Chalasani said.
Other applications could focus on muscle cells and insulin-producing cells, he added.
