Eight golden rules for living in a student dormitory
It has been 11 years since I moved into a student dormitory at the uninformed age of 19. Back then, I still believed in berets and moral relativism, but only now do I remember the forced smiles of the people I annoyed—and the numerous, long complaints about others.
Much of what I have learned can be summed up in eight simple rules.
Moving into a dorm can be anything from nerve-wracking to completely scary.
It's tempting to chatter: tell us where you're from, whether you took a gap year and where, what you think of Corbyn, and why "I seriously don't love or hate Marmite because really it's just yeast extract HAHAHA to find me in my room".
Take a breath.
And also help others take a breath - ask questions and show interest.
It guides the conversation and helps you find the people you like, not the ones you don't want to talk to, even if your eyelashes are on fire and they're handing out fire extinguishers.
Give people space.
People's rooms often turn into cocktail parties, movie nights, and general hangouts, but they're also the places where people dress and fix their underwear.
Related: Don't even imagine starting college while you're in a relationship
University is a tough place for introverts.
Your room should be a resting place, but many dorms develop a culture of wandering from room to room that is friendly, social, and causes lifelong friendships.
It could mean hell for someone trying to rest.
Nothing in this culture gives you permission to say "I like you and want to be friends with you, but you have to leave now so that I can regain the energy I spent in conversation with you".
Try to sense when a fellow student is tired of socializing - and maybe text instead of knocking on the door.
From knocking when the talk came: knock.
One guy in my student dorm thought that if the door wasn't locked, he had been invited in.
He saw quite a few things.
Make friends through baking.
Since you're starting college at the peak of the baking trend, knocking on people's doors with a plate of chocolates and introducing yourself seems somewhat less weird, less "welcome to the neighborhood, I baked something for you, now smile when I ask you personal questions" from a '50s.
Serving homemade treats is a great way to make friends.
Your roommates feel obligated to talk, and they may associate your face with a tasty surprise in the future.
Of course, this depends on whether you know how to bake.
Poorly mixed blobs of flour-sugar-fat are likely to make people just pretend to sleep when you knock.
Stealing food is a common crime in student dormitories.
Understandably, taking someone's chicken is stealing, but what if you just take a drop of milk into your tea?
Ask and check with the owner of the milk.
It's quite possible that they'll give you permission, even if they're boiling internally.
If someone steals your stuff, it's annoying and you'll get my sympathy — but try to treat it more adultly than my dorm buddy who mixed his milk with detergent to punish those who stole it.
He is now in prison.
You shouldn't make noise so that people can't sleep or study.
Not just to be a decent person, but because you're like that proverbial cauldron blaming the kettle.
