Sixten Korkman wrote a chapter in the book The Topicality of Capital: "Marx is worth getting to know"
The crises of the world economy have brought to the surface Karl Marx (1818-1883) and his main work Capital, published between 1867 and 1894, writes Yrjö Hakanen, known as the former chairman of the Communist Party of Finland, in Marx's book The Topicality of Capital, which is published today.
"He is being taken more seriously now than it has been for a long time," Hakanen writes in his foreword.
Marx's assessments of the development, internationalization and penetration of the capitalist economy into all spheres of life, the concentration of capital, and the growing role of money capital and imaginary capital have proved to be strikingly far-sighted.
Based on the Capital seminars organised by Hakanen, the list of authors also includes Aalto University professor and respected financial expert Sixten Korkman.
In the book, Korkman writes that Marx is topical "now and forever".
Surely the former Managing Director of the Research Institute of the Finnish Economy and the Finnish Business Delegation is not a Marxist?
Not at all.
Korkman says over the phone that he does not consider Marx to be a topical economic thinker, but rather an interesting social theorist.
Today, the social sciences are differentiated and specialized, but Marx was a philosopher, historian, sociologist, economist, journalist, political agitator, and literary connoisseur.
"The usual belief is that ideological history is about the wrong opinions of dead men," Korkman begins.
It is true that Marx's predictions went terribly wrong.
Although Marx understood the nature and significance of the Industrial Revolution, he drew too far-reaching conclusions from the early days of capitalism, Korkman reflects.
But Korkman sees value in Marx's radical attitude.
"What's more relevant about Marx is that he asked good questions," he says.
Now we are again discussing Marx's interests, such as the distribution of wealth.
"Marx can perhaps provide inspiration for those who want to understand the big picture, the changing world as a result of technological upheaval," Korkman analyses.
But what the government should decide tomorrow is of no help to Marx.
In his view, capitalism was a hopeless case that should just be stopped.
Still, Korkman thinks Marx is worth getting to know.
"In the '70s, Marx couldn't be read," Korkman says.
"Maoists and Trotskyists and other sects all hated capitalism, but even more so each other".
Today, the debate is more diverse, and Marx can also be approached without the ideological and political baggage of the past.
"Every social scientist should be familiar with Marx's way of thinking – just like any other classic," Korkman says.
