Guests arrive from the mainland to the Kerkenna Islands in small groups.
The Emir accommodates them in empty houses for as long as he sees fit.
Food is given in such a way that customers barely survive.
Accommodation costs around 75 euros per night, and if a customer runs out of money, that's their problem.
The boat is launched at midnight with extinguished lanterns.
The first night you drive away from the islands, then stop, wait for the day and drive the next night to Lampedusa.
Sometimes the sea is rough, and in waves 20 meters high, passengers cry and vomit.
At the destination, the human cargo is unloaded in half an hour and the Emir departs for the return journey.
The emir wants to be feared.
That's why he beats his customers and at least claims to beat them to death.
He says in the book that once the police caught up with him, he threw all his passengers overboard and told them to swim to the nearest island.
