Tom is a novice smuggler, former drug courier.
An Irishman in his forties is on duty on the French coast in Calais, where his job is to load people onto lorries bound for Britain.
He has the help of an Afghan living in London, a French taxi driver, and dozens of truckers who may not even know they are in the human smuggling business.
At night, Tom and the taxi driver pick up their customers, usually 2-3 people, somewhere near the centre of Calais.
They drive on the A26 motorway and try to evade the police.
If the police stopped the car on the highway, Tom and the driver would go directly to jail for arranging illegal immigration.
That's not what Tom wants, he's been sitting for seven years now because of drugs.
Stopped by a taxi, Tom and his customers run across the motorway to a rest area where the drivers sleep before continuing across the Channel to Britain.
Tom chooses a suitable truck - you have to make sure it's going to England and not, say, Holland - and cuts the safety cable on the tarpaulin.
It must be done quietly so that the drivers do not wake up.
Sometimes the driver is involved in the plot, but then the hustle and bustle is more expensive.
When the route is clear, Tom wraps his customers in aluminum foil, the same kind that is wrapped around a roast or baked potato in the kitchen.
It should prevent the police thermal scanner from spotting the hiding person.
Some use a sleeping bag filled with ice for the same purpose.
Tom leaves his customers in the truck and leaves, hoping that the driver won't catch stowaways, at least not before Britain.
King of smugglers
Muammer Küçük is one of the world's most famous people smugglers.
The ultra-rich Turk has been called a marketing champion and the undisputed king of illegal landings in the Mediterranean, controlling sea routes from Turkey to EU countries, mainly Greece and Italy.
