Sipilä takes a big risk
The media researcher hopes that Sipilä's televised speech does not indicate a more general introversion of the government.
Is there an attempt to take the right to define public debate more firmly into one's own hands and refuse to raise questions in public debate? ponders Professor Anu Koivunen from Stockholm University.
I am reminded of Foreign Minister (Timo) Soini's recent comment that he does not follow the media's agenda and does not let it define him.
In the interests of democratic debate and publicity, I hope that these issues are not linked.
Koivunen understands that the commercial media is indignant about Sipilä's announcement.
It would be strange if the media field did not react.
The communication styles of political decision-makers are not matters of revelation in a democracy.
By definition, the task of media representatives is to try not to take politicians' agendas as given.
According to Koivunen, televised speech is a big risk for Sipilä.
In his speech, Sipilä should bring something new and special to the table in order to meet the exceptionally high expectations set for the speech.
Is there more of what we have already heard today?
Or will they be able to speak in a different tone, in a different way, with different words, or say something new?
Koivunen says that if there will only be more of the same old stuff, one has to wonder why such a grand gesture was made and Yle gave it exceptional time.
Yle also takes a risk here in the sense that it is not a special situation but a routine speech among others.
There is a risk that Yle will be labelled as the media of politicians or Parliament and the government, which is certainly not in line with Yle's interests or general policy.
A clever bet from Sipilä
In Sipilä's upcoming speech, it is also important what the Prime Minister leaves unsaid, the media researcher emphasises.
In the evening, we need to look carefully at what Sipilä is missing and what is not," says Heikki Kuutti, Research Coordinator at the University of Jyväskylä.
According to Kuutti, a TV speech is a clever move for Sipilä, because it allows him to express his own point of view without dissenting voices.
