The US Fed will next try to tighten monetary policy
The next recession in the United States will begin at its fastest in less than a year, but more likely within three years after the Fed, the country's central bank, starts raising interest rates again after a long time.
And in the financial markets, the downturn will begin before the next recession.
The Fed has hinted that it may begin raising interest rates as early as this week and at the latest by the end of the year.
As a result, the next recession may weigh on at its fastest by next autumn and the financial markets will fluctuate before that.
Or at least that's what will happen if the world's largest economy and financial markets act the way they used to—and if they react to the Fed's tightening of the money taps as they have done in the past.
These are the conclusions reached by Jim Reid, Nick Burns and Seb Barker, strategists at Deutsche Bank's London Market Research at German bank Deutsche Bank, in their extensive study of long-term market and economic cycles.
The bank distributed a more than 60-page Long-Term Asset Return Study report to major international customers last week.
The strategists who produced the study and the report do not pretend to know exactly when the Fed will start raising interest rates or what will happen in the economy and markets after that.
Instead, they use cool facts from economic statistics and their calculations to show how the economy and markets have behaved in the past during and after the Fed's rate hikes.
In addition to historical observations, they look at which key variables in the economy and financial markets are now in the same or different pattern as they were during previous rate hikes – and what the possible consequences might be.
It becomes clear that both the economy and financial markets are now in a more shaky condition to withstand rising interest rates than at any time since the 1950s.
Maybe not even a year before the start of the recession
Throughout last summer and early fall, the Fed's monetary policy and its current stance leaders have hinted that the time is ripe to raise interest rates.
The first rate hike in more than nine years could come as early as this week.
The matter will be resolved on Wednesday and Thursday when the Fed's board of directors' so-called open market committee meets to decide on the matter for its two-day meeting.
The last time the Fed raised its key interest rate was in June 2006.
That marked the end of a two-year series of relatively regular, but small 0.25 percentage point rate hikes at a time, with which the Fed raised its interest rate from 1.25% to 5.25%.
The financial market turmoil began in 2007 with the difficulties of the riskiest housing financing in the United States, and a year later the financial crisis erupted into a global doomsday nightmare.
The Great Recession came in 2009.
Last time, severe setbacks in the financial markets and the real economy started more slowly than has typically happened after previous Fed rate hikes.
Correspondingly, the trials were tougher and harsher than at any time since the depression of the 1930s.
Deutsche's strategists have screened the ups and downs of the world's largest economies and financial market turnarounds since the 1950s and in some places since the early 1800s.
They report on the Fed's interest rate hikes and their economic and financial impact since the 1950s.
At its fastest, less than a year has passed since the first interest rate hike began, usually less than three years and an average of less than three and a half years.
The rise in financial markets has ended within a year or two of the start of the Fed's rate hikes.
Since the early 1950s, the Fed has alternately raised and lowered its key interest rate by a dozen cycles of varying lengths.
Each time has differed in some respects from the other, and the number of times examined is relatively sparse, so it is hardly possible to conclude anything definite about the effects of the next interest rate hikes.
The strategists remind us that many things are different this time.
And not just better.
Interest rates too low for too long
The decisive causes of the financial crisis, let alone the culprits, may not be unquestionably unclear, even after decades of research.
But three things about the reasons that led to the crisis and increased its destructive power are more or less undeniable:
1) In the 2000s, the Fed, the euro area ECB and other major central banks in the world kept their key interest rates too low for too long.
They patched up traces of the tech bubble, and at the same time increased the next one.
2) The already excessive amount of debt accumulated over the decades in different parts of the financial and real economy grew even larger as a result of the overly loose monetary policy of central banks.
The largest debt bubble in economic history up to that point was created.
3) In particular, the crazy cheap debt financing, which was almost unrestrained in the financial economy, inflated most sectors of the financial markets with the largest price bubbles in economic history up to that point, from equities to real estate, bonds and commodities.
Nor is there likely to be a very harsh dispute that financial markets, which have risen to heights on increasingly complex leverage, were in an unusually dangerous and volatile state when the Fed and other central banks last pushed interest rates up.
Financial structures tuned on leverage, let alone valuation bubbles, only lasted for a long time after interest rate hikes had begun and the cost of debt financing had started to rise.
The risks materialised in the form of the financial crisis, followed by the Great Recession.
Bigger bubble and more debt
Deutsche's strategists don't speculate on what will happen next, but give some food for thought by mentioning things like:
1) The Fed and other major central banks have now kept their monetary policy stance even more accommodative for even longer than before the financial crisis.
If interest rates were too low for too long before the crisis, they have now been even lower for even longer.
2) For a long time, debt has not been madly cheap as it was ten years ago, but now debt money is literally cheaper than free at its cheapest.
As a result, the debt load of the financial and real economy has not eased, but there is now a much heavier debt load in different parts of the economy than before or ever before the financial crisis.
3) Liquidity from central banks has largely remained in the financial markets, pushing key asset and asset classes to their highest levels since the peak before the financial crisis or at any time.
Not only are strategists dampening sentiment with financial market warning signs, but they also point out that even the U.S. economy has not yet recovered from the financial crisis and the heaviest recession in decades as it has done in the past.
The euro area economy has barely recovered at all.
In other words, the real economy is in an unusually weak state, but correspondingly, the pressures and risks in the financial markets are incomparably greater than before the financial crisis, when the Fed next starts tightening its money taps.
Perhaps the future picture of Albert Edwards, strategist at the French bank Societe Generale, is not as strange as it might seem.
For some time now, he has been coaching the bank's international investor clients for the Fed's next U-turns:
First the Fed raises interest rates, then the financial bubbles burst - and soon it's time for the Fed to rush to extinguish the financial fires with even bigger QE injections.
