Federal Reserve policymakers will sit around a huge mahogany table for two days this week in a long-awaited meeting to decide whether the time has come to raise interest rates for the first time in nearly a decade.
At one end of the central bank's ornate, two-story meeting room is a mural from the United States.
The map is a reminder that Federal Reserve Chairman Janet L. Yellen and her colleagues must put the nation's economic interests above all else.
Congress has placed a dual responsibility on the central bank: to maximize U.S. employment and keep prices stable.
Since the Great Depression, however, central bank governors have accepted that there is also a third, unwritten mandate: economic stability.
It is this third requirement that could be the decisive factor in the decision to be announced on Thursday, which will be so strict that it cannot even be predicted. A decision on whether the U.S. economy is ready to wean itself off the record-breaking stimulus provided by short-term interest rates that have remained close to zero since late 2008.
While most of the data points to steady economic growth, the recent turmoil in global financial markets may have made already wary central bank officials even more frightened when it comes to increasing volatility. There are fears about what would happen if the federal funds rate reference value were raised by even a quarter of a percentage point.
"Understandably, the labor market and inflation are the first and most important issues to monitor," says Lindsey M. Piegza, chief financial adviser at brokerage firm Stifel Nicolaus &; Co.
"However, I believe that if they are looking for justification for leaving interest rates unchanged, the increased uncertainty in global markets is a valid enough reason to wait," he says.
There is no consensus on the Central Bank's decision, which in itself creates nervousness in the economy.
According to a recent Bloomberg survey, about half of economic experts predict that interest rates will rise this week.
Financial markets, on the other hand, expect the central bank to delay the hike, as a key indicator indicates that the potential for growth is only about 30 per cent.
This suggests a fall in the stock market if the central bank raises the level, unless policymakers manage to soften the blow by promising that the next hike will not happen anytime soon.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 228.89 points, or 1.4 percent, to a new figure of 16,599.85.
The recovery came with the expectation that the central bank will keep levels unchanged this week, according to John Lonski, chief economic adviser at Moody's Capital Markets Research Group.
"It's surprising if the central bank is raising interest rates right now," he says.
If policymakers raise interest rates, "they will have to go to great lengths to support financial markets so they don't panic."
Other experts argue that the elevated level would calm financial markets because it would remove uncertainty about when the central bank will act.
Just a month ago, it appeared that the central bank was about to raise interest rates by a quarter of a percentage point this month, thus taking the first small step towards a slow tightening of monetary conditions that would ensure the stability of the US recovery.
Yellen has stated in the spring and early summer that she expects the level to rise this year, despite Liberals calling for more economic development in their complaints.
Although job creation slowed in August, labour market growth has been steady this year.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1% last month, the lowest figure in seven years and close to what the central bank considers the threshold for full employment.
Wage growth has shown signs of recovery.
Although inflation is still below the central bank's 2% annual target, central bank policymakers say the main reason for this is the temporary effect of significantly lower oil prices.
The economy "can cope with higher interest rates and needs them given the tight conditions of the labour market," said Ian Shepherdson, chief economic adviser at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
However, financial markets around the world were shaken last week when China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones industrial average fell as much as 16 percent from its May record as investors feared China's slowing economy would also slow global growth.
The market has recovered somewhat this month, and the Dow is now nearly 10 percent below its May high.
For central bank policymakers, market turmoil is an additional factor in the complex equation of when interest rates should be raised.
"Without these financial market events and recent weeks' coverage of China's economic weakness, policymakers would tighten levels at this meeting," said Stephen D. Oliner, a senior investigator at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former central bank official.
Now, he predicts policymakers will wait at least a month to get a better understanding of the impact.
"The potential impact on the U.S. economy is still very unclear, and they don't have much data at their disposal regarding the consequences of what happened in China," Oliner said.
The well-being of the international economy is not one of the main concerns of the Central Bank, therefore, in principle, it should not influence decision-making.
However, in practice, the Federal Central Bank has become the world's monetary authority.
In recent years, the influence of the Central Bank has been enormous.
In 2013, the hint by then-chairman Ben S. Bernanke that the central bank could "narrow" the increase in the money supply caused upheaval in markets around the world.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly intertwined, central bank officials are expected not only to monitor developments elsewhere, but also to consult other central banks and experts to gain a better understanding of the global economy.
The central bank's decision-making process is "more of an art than a science," said Zachary Karabell, head of global strategy at asset management firm Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, chairman of the Federal Reserve Bank in Richmond, Virginia, noted this month that "the central bank has overreacted in the past to financial market movements that appear to be disconnected from economic fundamentals."
The Federal Open Market Committee, which makes decisions, has called for an interest rate increase, and Lacker, a voting member of the committee, cites the 1998-99 decisions as an example.
The Asian financial crisis caused the central bank to cut its reference value by 0.75 percentage points over three meetings "despite its limited, identifiable effects on U.S. economic growth," Lacker said.
A year later, the central bank reversed these cuts.
The central bank should only prioritise financial stability during a major crisis, such as when the markets crashed in 2008, said Adam S. Posen, a former member of the Bank of England's interest rate setting committee.
The latest turmoil is nowhere near that level, Posen says.
"No one wants to be in a situation where they are afraid of raising interest rates because the markets are upset," said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still contains a dual requirement and makes no mention of financial stability. As long as this is the case, I do not think they should anticipate it.
