Bariatric surgery can help mildly obese diabetics
According to a new study, the benefits of bariatric surgery for mildly obese type 2 diabetics can last at least five years.
However, it is still too early to say whether these mildly obese diabetics will live longer after bariatric surgery than those treated with other methods than surgery.
"It takes a long time to get mortality data," Dr. Robin Blackstone notes. She is a bariatric surgery expert who wrote an editorial for a new study in the journal JAMA Surgery.
Bariatric surgery uses different methods to reduce the size of the stomach.
They reduce the feeling of hunger and limit the absorption of food.
Over the years, bariatric surgeries have been found to be effective in treating type 2 diabetes, but most of the people in the study have been morbidly obese, with a body mass index (BMI) of 35 or more.
BMI, or the ratio of weight to height, is considered normal when it is between 18.5 and 24.9.
If the BMI is above 25, it indicates that someone is overweight, and if the person's BMI is over 30, they are considered obese.
You can calculate your BMI here: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For this new study, researchers at Min-Sheng General Hospital in Taiwan used data collected since 2007 to compare two types of bariatric surgery, gastric bypass surgery and gastric reduction, with medical treatments for type 2 diabetes in people who were mildly obese.
The study showed that the average BMI of people undergoing surgery dropped from 31 to 24.5 by the end of the fifth year.
At the same time, the BMI of people treated with means other than surgery remained roughly the same at 29.
In 36% of the operated individuals, diabetes was completely cured and 28% partially cured.
In comparison, in the medically treated group, diabetes was completely cured by only 1 percent and partially by about 2 percent.
In addition, blood pressure, triglycerides, as well as the "bad" LDL cholestor "were generally better in the surgical group," the authors noted.
The researchers also tracked patients' blood hemoglobin A1c levels, which mirror blood sugar levels over time.
Hemoglobin A1c should remain below 7 percent, the researchers write.
Postoperative hemoglobin A1c levels dropped from about 9% to about 6%.
However, in the drug treatment group, it remained stable at around 8%.
However, this improved "glycemic control," as described by improved hemoglobin A1c levels, did not reduce mortality over five years, said lead investigator Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and colleagues.
The research team also compared average results between two different types of surgery.
At year five, when compared with the gastric reduction group, the gastric bypass group had lost more weight (18.7 and 14.2 kg, respectively), decreased their BMI more (7.4 and 5.1), decreased their haemoglobin A1c levels more (3.1 percent and 2.1 percent, respectively), and was more likely to achieve complete diabetes remission (46.9 percent and 16.7 percent, respectively).
Blackstone of the University of Arizona's College of Medicine-Phoenix says that while the study shows no survival or surgery after five years, there are research findings from Sweden where surgery resulted in longer lives in heavier people.
A Swedish study found that obese people who underwent bariatric surgery were 29 percent less likely to die over a 15-year period when compared to a group that had tried more traditional treatments.
While the new study shows no improvement in survival among patients undergoing surgery, Blackstone says the results are nonetheless encouraging for individuals with BMI below 35 who are interested in surgery.
"The results of the study are crucial precisely because they show that surgery is safe for the lower BMI group," and is not associated with an increased risk of death or kidney disease, he says.
Blackstone adds that both patients and their doctors should take weight very seriously when the patient's BMI is between 27 and 30.
"I think we're waiting too long before we take this seriously," he says.
I believe that once a person has accumulated these genetic changes that permanently prepare his body for obesity and diabetes, it will be very difficult to reverse the situation.
