Glencore raises $2.5 billion through stock sales
Switzerland-based mining giant Glencore, which suffered a commodity price crash, raised $2.5 billion on Wednesday by selling shares as part of its sweeping debt cutting plan.
Glencore, which is listed on the London Stock Exchange, said in a statement that it had sold new shares worth around £1.6 billion to repay its debt.
The company, which lost 57% of its market value this year, is struggling with plummeting commodity prices as China's economic slowdown weighs on demand and wreaks havoc on all markets.
The rights issue pushed the value of Glencore's shares to the top of the London Stock Exchange in Wednesday's morning trading.
Shares rose 2.77 per cent to 131.60 pence on the FTSE 100 index, which opened 0.69 per cent higher.
Glencore had unveiled a $2.5 billion stock deal the previous week as part of a broader plan to cut its $30 billion debt burden by about a third.
The company sold new equity for 125p a share, representing a 2.4% discount on Tuesday's closing price.
The company sold 1.3 billion shares, which together accounted for 9.99 percent of the group.
Concerns about a prolonged halt in China's growth have cut iron ore prices by about half, while coal, copper and other commodity prices have fallen by 20 to 40 percent.
White House confirms Xi Jinping's visit to Washington
Chinese President Xi Jinping will make a state visit to the United States at the end of the month, a White House statement released Tuesday confirmed.
Xi's first official visit to Washington will take place on September 25 and is a response to President Barack Obama's visit to Beijing last November, the statement said.
The President of the United States and Michelle Obama, the President's spouse, will host a dinner for Xi and his spouse Peng Liyuan after the leaders hold bilateral talks.
"Preident Xi's visit will provide an opportunity to expand U.S.-China cooperation on a wide range of global, regional, and bilateral issues of mutual interest, while at the same time allowing President Obama and President Xi to engage constructively on issues of disagreement," it added.
During the visit, which was first announced in February, Xi is also expected to make a stop in Seattle on his trip to Washington to meet with numerous U.S. technology leaders before heading to New York City and the UN General Assembly in September.
Obama and Xi are expected to discuss a number of controversial topics, including Washington's concerns over China's alleged cyber espionage and the country's increased absolutism in the disputed waters of the South China Sea.
Matt Damon downplays diversity in filmmaking
Matt Damon clashed with African-American filmmaker Effie Brown as they discussed the difference, which Damon says is not needed behind the scenes.
On Sunday night's episode of HBO's Project Greenlight, the veteran actor interrupted Brown as he emphasized the need for different perspectives on the dark-skinned protagonist of the script chosen for the project.
"When we talk about diversity, it's taken into account when choosing actors for a movie, not a series," Damon argued.
A shocked Brown reacted with hurtful disbelief, commenting, "Oops! Wow. Okay," while the comments from The Martian actor were left hanging in the air.
Co-producers Ben Affleck and the Farrelly brothers joined Damon and Brown to discuss the show's finalists.
"I want to encourage people to think, whoever the director is, how they treat Harmony's character," Brown said at the beginning.
The only dark figure is a whore beaten by her white pimp.
The producer of The Dear White People claimed the rights to direct the film for finalists Leo Angelos and Kristen Brancaccio; Damon bluntly replied that their guidance "could end up giving us something we don't want."
After the conversation was posted, social media exploded into outrage at Damon's comments.
Twitter user MrPooni expressed his anger at the film clip, writing, "Matt Damon talking over the only black person in the room and explaining to him the difference is SO WHITE it hurts."
The tweet garnered over 5000 retweets and 4000 likes since its release.
Damon's comments come at a time when accurate racial representation in the media is at the forefront of social debate.
After teenager Michael Brown was killed by white police in 2014, The Black Lives Matter movement spread nationwide, calling on lawmakers and authorities to end discriminatory practices against people of color.
In February, singer Prince alluded to the movement when presenting the nominees for Album of the Year for the Grammy Award.
"Albums still matter," he said.
Like books and Black lives, albums still matter.
Leaders of the Black Lives Matter movement recently released a statement in response to a question from Fox News television face Elisabeth Hasselbeck about whether the group should be considered a hate group.
"The Black Lives Matter Network is a love group," executives said.
It was recently reported that Damon will be among the entertainers, producers and media moguls invited to visit the Pope to discuss the image of the Catholic Church in the West.
It is unclear whether he has accepted the invitation or already met with the Pope.
First American Ninja Warrior Champion Crowned
Professional rock climber and dish collector Isaac Caldiero on Monday became the first athlete to win the American Ninja Warrior competition, receiving a million-dollar grand prize as a reward.
The competition show, which has just finished its seventh season, has never had a competitor who has survived all sections of the show's obstacle course.
In the final episode of the series, two men, Caldiero and cameraman Geoff Britten, made it to the final round.
The last task involved climbing a rope of about 23 meters in 30 seconds.
Britten climbed first and cleared the challenge on time, making him the first athlete ever to complete the grueling 4th leg of American Ninja Warrior. However, Caldiero cleared the challenge three seconds faster, making him the winner.
Caldiero gave an interview to E! After the hard-won win for the News and was still in shock at winning the million-dollar grand prize.
"So it's amazing to think about this when I've never made or lived on more than $10,000 a year," Isaac told E! after his big raise.
So all of a sudden... So I can't even imagine what this is going to be like... The future is unknown.
Production director Kent Weed sat down with The Hollywood Reporter to talk about fiinal and why Britten isn't getting more paid despite being the first racer ever to make it through the track.
According to the rules, money goes to the fastest person.
"If more people pass, the money goes to whoever has the fastest time," Weed said.
Although money is a great reward and life-changing, he still gets a great sense of satisfaction.
I don't think he feels a grudge for that.
He's just so happy that he's been able to do what he did.
His fans have praised him.
He's a great guy and a good family man.
He is the hero of his children and wife.
Geoff told me, "If someone had to beat me, I'm happy it was Isaac."
