Xi calls for wider global opening of the economy
The economy must open up more to the outside world to boost growth, President Xi Jinping told a group tasked with guiding the reform on Tuesday.
"China should commit to attracting foreign funding and expertise and developing a policy of transparency," he said, speaking at the 16th meeting of the group leading the deepening of the overall reform.
Supporting openness while advancing reforms will increase new movement and vitality, and create new space for economic growth, Xi said.
The steering group adopted a series of guidelines, including a negative list restricting market access, a relaxation of border control principles, an invitation to private capital for state-owned enterprises, and a review of the resident registration system.
According to the opinion, a negative list will be created naming the sectors and companies in which investment is not allowed.
The system will be gradually tested and improved through pilot programmes.
The change is significant as it gives the market a greater role in resource allocation, ensures a legal business environment and makes the market more transparent, the statement said.
The government is also loosening its control over the power it distributes to companies, thus ensuring that companies decide for themselves how to run their businesses.
The statement also said that China will allow border regions to explore new models of cross-border economic cooperation and new mechanisms for developing regional growth.
In order to open up state-controlled sectors, more sectors will open up to private financiers.
"The government will not change its policy on foreign investment and will protect the legitimate interests of foreign-funded companies and provide them with better services," the statement said.
In addition, the application process for foreign permanent resident permits, or "green cards", will be facilitated by optimising the requirements and streamlining the application process.
The meeting also discussed guaranteeing the professional rights of lawyers and supporting professional judges and prosecutors.
The meeting was also attended by Premier Li Keqiang, as well as senior leaders Liu Yunshan and Zhang Gaoli, a statement released after the meeting said.
